<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
The presence of cordiform fruits is the most remarkable character to distinguish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huan C. Wang, Shao Y. Liu &amp; Z. T. Ren" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hemilophia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemilophia cardiocarpa" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Hemilophia cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other species of this genus. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. cardiocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. rockii" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="rockii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. rockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Hemilophia rockii A acauline leaf showing adaxial face B cauline leaf showing abaxial face C a portion of infructescence D fruit." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.194.82737.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673787" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">4</figureCitation>
) in having a similar habit and sharing similar indumentum, leaf shape, as well as flower size and arrangement. Nevertheless, it clearly differs from the latter by its cauline leaves usually ovate, rarely obovate or oblong (vs. oblanceolate to narrowly elliptic, or rarely ovate in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. rockii" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="rockii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. rockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 5-8 mm (vs. 3-4 (6)) long, 2-4 mm (vs. 1-1.5 (3)) wide, racemes usually 5-13 (vs. 5-6) -flowered, pedicels of fruits shorter than or nearly equal to its leaflike bract (vs. significantly longer than leaflike bract) and fruit cordate (vs. spindle or narrowly oblong) in shape. 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. cardiocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar to the type species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. pulchella" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Franch., from which it is readily distinguished by the racemes usually 5-13-flowered (vs. 2-3-flowered in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. pulchella" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and petals bluish-white to white (vs. pink), 4-7 mm (vs. 2.5-3.5 mm) long, 2-3.5 mm (vs. 1.5-2 mm) wide. Taxa of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hemilophia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemilophia" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Hemilophia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished through the morphological characters presented in the following identification key modified from 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" author="Al-Shehbaz, IA" journalOrPublisher="Adansonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" refId="B2" refString="Al-Shehbaz, IA, 2002. New combinations in Brassicaceae (Cruciferae): Draba serpens is a Hemilophia and D. williamsii is a Lepidostemon. Edinburgh Journal of Botany 59(03): 443-446. https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" title="New combinations in Brassicaceae (Cruciferae): Draba serpens is a Hemilophia and D. williamsii is a Lepidostemon. Edinburgh Journal of Botany 59 (03): 443 - 446." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" year="2002">Al-Shehbaz (2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Al-Shehbaz, IA" editor="Hong, DY" journalOrPublisher="30. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, and Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="1 - 595" refId="B4" refString="Al-Shehbaz, IA, 2015. Brassicaceae. In: Hong, DY, Ed., Flora of Pan-Himalaya vol. 30. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, and Science Press, Beijing: 1 - 595" title="Brassicaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Pan-Himalaya vol." year="2015">2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
